b'[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe0216.htm)  [Next](sbe0218.htm)\n\n* * *\n\np. 51\n\n### PRA _S_ NA I, PA _T_ ALA 4, KHA _N_ _D_ A 14.\n\n1\\. (That is to say) the Agnihotra, hospitality, 1\n\n2\\. And what else of this kind (is ordained).\n\n3\\. He whom (a student) asks for instruction, shall certainly not refuse it; 3\n\n4\\. Provided he does not see in him a fault, (which disqualifies him from\nbeing taught).\n\n5\\. If by chance (through the pupil\'s stupidity the teaching) is not\ncompleted, obedience towards the (teacher is the pupil\'s only refuge). 5\n\n6\\. Towards a mother (grandmother and great-grandmother) and a father\n(grandfather and great-grandfather) the same obedience must be shown as\ntowards a teacher. 6\n\n7\\. The feet of all Gurus must be embraced (every day) by a student who has\nreturned home; 7\n\n8\\. And also on meeting them, after returning from a journey. 8\n\n9\\. The feet of (elder) brothers and sisters must be embraced, according to\nthe order of their seniority. 9\n\n10\\. And respect (must) always (be shown to one\'s elders and betters),\naccording to the injunction 10\n\np. 52\n\n[paragraph continues] (given above and according to the order of their\nseniority).\n\n11\\. He shall salute an officiating priest, a father-in-law, a father\'s\nbrother, and a mother\'s. brother, (though they may be) younger than he\nhimself, and (when saluting) rise to meet them. 11\n\n12\\. Or he may silently embrace their feet. 12\n\n13\\. A friendship kept for ten years with fellow citizens (is a reason for\ngiving a salutation, and so is) a friendship, contracted at school, which has\nlasted for five years. But a learned Brahma _n_ a (known) for less than three\nyears, must be saluted. 13\n\n14\\. If the age (of several persons whom one meets) is exactly known, one must\nsalute the eldest (first).\n\n15\\. He need not salute a person, who is not a Guru, and who stands in a lower\nor higher place than he himself.\n\n16\\. Or he may descend or ascend (to the place where such a person stands) and\nsalute him. 16\n\n17\\. But every one (Gurus and others) he shall salute, after having risen\n(from his seat). 17\n\n18\\. If he is impure, he shall not salute (anybody); 18\n\n19\\. (Nor shall he salute) a person who is impure.\n\np. 53\n\n20\\. Nor shall he, being impure, return a salutation.\n\n21\\. Married women (must be saluted) according to the (respective) ages of\ntheir husbands.\n\n22\\. He shall not salute with his shoes on, or his head wrapped up, or his\nhands full.\n\n23\\. In saluting women, a Kshatriya or a Vai _s_ ya he shall use a pronoun,\nnot his name. 23\n\n24\\. Some (declare, that he shall salute in this manner even) his mother and\nthe wife of his teacher. 24\n\n25\\. Know that a Brahma _n_ a of ten years and a Kshatriya of a hundred years\nstand to each other in the relation of father and son. But between those two\nthe Brahma _n_ a is the father. 25\n\n26\\. A younger person or one of equal age he shall ask, about his well-being\n(employing the word ku _s_ ala). 26\n\n27\\. (He shall ask under the same conditions) a Kshatriya, about his health\n(employing the word anamaya);\n\n28\\. A Vai _s_ ya if he has lost anything (employing the word anash _t_ a). 28\n\np. 54\n\n29\\. A _S_ udra, about his health (employing the word arogya).\n\n30\\. He shall not pass a learned Brahma _n_ a without addressing him;\n\n31\\. Nor an (unprotected) woman in a forest (or any other lonely place). 31\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[51:1](sbe0217.htm#fr_322) **14**. The Agnihotra, i.e. certain daily oblations\nof clarified butter.\n\n[51:3](sbe0217.htm#fr_323) Manu II, 109-115.\n\n[51:5](sbe0217.htm#fr_324) Manu II, 218.\n\n[51:6](sbe0217.htm#fr_325) Manu II, 228, 215.\n\n[51:7](sbe0217.htm#fr_326) The word Gurus, \'venerable persons,\' includes\nbesides the teacher and persons mentioned in the preceding Sutra, an elder\nbrother, a maternal uncle, and all others who are one\'s betters or elders. See\nabove, I, 2, 6, 29-35.\n\n[51:8](sbe0217.htm#fr_327) \'That is to say, whether he himself or "the\nvenerable persons" undertook the journey.\'--Haradatta.\n\n[51:9](sbe0217.htm#fr_328) Manu II, 133.\n\n[51:10](sbe0217.htm#fr_329) See above, I, 4, 13, 2.\n\n[52:11](sbe0217.htm#fr_330) Manu II, 130.\n\n[52:12](sbe0217.htm#fr_331) The commentator adds that the mode of salutation\nmust depend on their learning and virtue,\n\n[52:13](sbe0217.htm#fr_332) Manu II, 134.\n\n[52:16](sbe0217.htm#fr_333) This Sutra, like the preceding, refers to those\nwho are not \'Gurus.\'\n\n[52:17](sbe0217.htm#fr_334) Manu II, 120.\n\n[52:18](sbe0217.htm#fr_335) \'Impure,\' i.e. unfit for associating with others\non account of the death of relations or through other causes, see below, I, 5,\n15, 7 seq.\n\n[53:23](sbe0217.htm#fr_336) He shall say, \'I salute,\' not \'I, N. N., salute.\'\nManu II, 123.\n\n[53:24](sbe0217.htm#fr_337) \xc3\x82pastamba, of course, holds the contrary opinion.\nManu II, 216.\n\n[53:25](sbe0217.htm#fr_338) This verse, which is found with slight variations\nin most Sm _ri_ tis contains, according to Haradatta, an instruction given by\na teacher to his pupil. Manu II, 135.\n\n[53:26](sbe0217.htm#fr_339) Of course. in case the person addressed is a\nBrahman. Manu II, 127. Kulluka quotes under this verse the above and the\nfollowing Sutras. But his quotation has only a faint resemblance to our text.\n\n[53:28](sbe0217.htm#fr_340) That is to say in these terms I hope you have not\nlost any cattle or other property!\'--Haradatta.\n\n[54:31](sbe0217.htm#fr_341) He shall address a woman in order to re-assure\nher, and do it in these terms: \'Mother, or sister, what can I do for you?\nDon\'t be afraid!\' &c.--Haradatta.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: Pra _s_ na I, Pa _t_ ala 5, Kha _n_ _d_ a 15](sbe0218.htm)\n\n'